76. Sniffin’ Glue (1976–77), Mark Perry’s iconic punk fanzine, was but the first of many, paving the way for hundreds of home-made magazines to be cut and pasted in bedrooms across the UK. From these, glimpses into provincial cultures, teenage style wars and formative political ideas may be gleaned. An alternative history, away from the often-condescending glare of London’s media and music industry, can be formulated, drawn from such titles as Ripped & Torn, Brass Lip, City Fun, Vague, Kill Your Pet Puppy, Toxic Grafity, Hungry Beat and Hard as Nails. The first book of its kind, this collection reveals the contested nature of punk’s cultural politics by turning the pages of a vibrant underground press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCounterculturevFanzines. 0aCounterculture. 0aFan magazinesxPolitical aspectszGreat BritainxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aMusic and rhetoricy20th century. 0aMusic and rhetoric. 0aPolitics and culturey20th century. 0aPolitics and culture. 0aPopular culturevMusicvFanzinesy1976. 0aPopular culture. 0aPunk culturexPolitical aspectszGreat Britainy20th century. 0aPunk culturey1976. 0aPunk culture. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2020. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aCounterculture.  aFanzines.  aPolitics.  aPopular Music.  aPunk.  aSubculture.1 aBaines, Jess, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBestley, Russ, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBinns, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBland, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlasé, Cazz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBullen, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a